{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"88e2541e-b1d0-401c-9dda-3ccec1024a15","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — the OS automatically generates them:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. They contain the stack trace, signal info, and thread state.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check under **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — for additional context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest starting point — no setup required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3ae28f0f-846a-4f78-9b35-914b526c230c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":301,"requestId":"A0D4:6C08C:A1DC6A:C41102:6A013671"},"id":"b1d4dcaf-7e6e-49f8-8ee9-0369752d117c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:52:58.581Z","parentId":"a725f765-3428-4853-9dbc-1c5c02d345b8"}
